## STRIPE TREASURY (Charm Wallet / merchant balance)
- **Integration:** Stripe Connect + Treasury (Financial Accounts, inbound/outbound transfers).
- **Service:** `src/lib/services/stripe-service.ts` — Connect onboarding, balance, transactions, outbound transfer, NMI settlement credit hook.
- **Client:** `src/lib/stripe.ts` — server-only Stripe SDK; **never** import in client components.
- **Types:** `src/types/stripe.ts`
- **Status:** Sandbox — live Treasury API calls are **commented** until Treasury access is approved on the platform account. **Demo stubs** return realistic data when `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` is unset or Treasury is not wired.
- **Live switch:** Remove `TODO` blocks and uncomment Stripe Treasury calls in `stripe-service.ts` when approved.
- **Rules:**
  - `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` **never** exposed to the client; **never** use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` on secret keys.
  - All Stripe calls **server-side only** (API routes, server actions, `stripe-service.ts`).
  - `WalletTransferForm` requires **explicit confirmation** (checkbox) before transfer; never auto-submit.
  - FDIC / sponsor-bank copy on wallet UI where balances are shown (`/wallet` marketing, `/dashboard/wallet`).
  - Use `formatCurrency` from `src/lib/utils` for displayed dollar amounts; Stripe amounts in API remain in **cents** where applicable.

RULES:
- Build must complete zero errors.
- Static generation step shows **59/59** (Next.js internal batch) — it increases when
  static routes are added; do not treat this N as the ○ route count (use the table above).
- All marketing pages must remain ○ static.
- All dashboard and API routes must remain ƒ dynamic.
- Dashboard routes MUST be dynamic (ƒ) — they require
  live session data. Never attempt to make them static.
- API routes MUST be dynamic (ƒ) — they handle POST
  requests. Never attempt to make them static.
- All marketing pages MUST be static (○) — no session
  required, no 'use client' on page.tsx files.
- "Generating static pages (N/N)" in build output is
  Next.js internal batch count — do NOT equate N to
  the number of ○ routes. Use the route table instead.
- If a marketing page.tsx becomes dynamic unexpectedly,
  find and remove any hook, cookie, or session call
  that forced it dynamic.
- The correct assertion for CI is: marketing static routes
  show ○ in the build table. Not a specific N count for
  “Generating static pages”.

## OOMA + PIPEDRIVE INTEGRATION

Auto-sync flow:
Lead created → syncLeadToPipedrive() → Person + Org + Deal
Phone clicked → formatDialLink() → Ooma dial
Call logged → POST /api/integrations/ooma → logCallActivity()
Note added → addNoteToDeal() → Pipedrive deal

Environment variables required:
PIPEDRIVE_API_TOKEN — Pipedrive personal API token
PIPEDRIVE_DOMAIN — e.g. yourcompany.pipedrive.com
OOMA_EXTENSION — Ooma Office extension number
OOMA_ACCOUNT_ID — Ooma account ID for web dial links

Rules:
- Never expose PIPEDRIVE_API_TOKEN to the client
- Never use NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix on integration tokens
- All Pipedrive calls go through src/lib/integrations/pipedrive.ts
- All Ooma formatting goes through src/lib/integrations/ooma.ts
- If API token is missing, log server-side only — never expose
  the missing token error to the client response
- Leads dashboard uses a client child component (leads-dashboard-client.tsx)
  for call log onClick; page.tsx remains a Server Component for data load

### CHARM DASHBOARD — TONE AND UI RULES

Dashboard pages are utility-first. No marketing copy, no section labels, no hero sections, no gradient-text. Typography is gray-900 headings, gray-500 subtext, white on dark sidebar. Data is the hero — tables, stat cards, and charts get maximum breathing room. CTAs in the dashboard are functional (Export, Retry, Dispute) never promotional. The compliance disclaimer does not appear in dashboard views.
